1. Project Overview Business Context & Objectives

In this project, I analyze real-world banking transaction data using Databricks SQL to extract meaningful insights that support a future customer segmentation model (deep learning / clustering). The goal is to understand spending behaviors, identify unusual patterns, and generate actionable recommendations.

The analysis follows a structured data analytics workflow:

Data exploration & profiling

Data quality assessment

Statistical analysis & outlier detection

Behavioral segmentation using categories & merchant information

Business interpretation of patterns and anomalies

This approach mirrors how a Data Analyst or Data Scientist would work in production within a financial institution.

Source : Financial Transactions Dataset (www.Kaggle.com)

Overview : This comprehensive financial dataset combines transaction records, customer information, and card data from a banking institution, spanning across the 2010s decade.

Dataset Information

1. Transaction Data

* Detailed transaction records including amounts, timestamps, and merchant details
* Covers transactions throughout the 2010s
* Features transaction types, amounts, and merchant information
* Perfect for analyzing spending patterns and building fraud detection models

* Standard classification codes for business types
* Enables transaction categorization and spending analysis
* Industry-standard MCC codes with descriptions

Data Quality

3.1. I want to display the columns with empty values.

For this task, using SQL, I will have to query tables column by column, which can take time.

So I chose to query tables in Databricks from the notebook using Spark.

Below the used Script

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, lit, count, when, array, struct, explode from functools import reduce

1. LIST OF TABLE TO BE VERIFIED

TABLES_TO_VERIFY = [ "workspace.portfolio.cards_data", "workspace.portfolio.mcc_codes", "workspace.portfolio.transactions_data", "workspace.portfolio.users_data" ]

all_results = []

2. ANALYSIS

for nom_table_complet in TABLES_TO_VERIFY: print(f"--- Analysis table : {nom_table_complet} ---")

try:
    df = spark.table(nom_table_complet)
except Exception as e:
    print(f"WARNING: Error loadind table {nom_table_complet}. Error : {e}")
    continue

3. CREATION OF NULL_COUNT

agg_exprs = [
    count(when(col(c).isNull(), c)).alias(f"null_count_{c}")
    for c in df.columns
]

null_counts_wide_df = df.agg(*agg_exprs)

4. REPORT CREATION

null_counts_long_df = null_counts_wide_df.select(
    explode(array(*[
        struct(lit(c).alias("column_name"), col(f"null_count_{c}").alias("null_count"))
        for c in df.columns
    ])).alias("col_data")
).select(
    col("col_data.column_name"),
    col("col_data.null_count")
).withColumn(
    "table_name", lit(nom_table_complet)
)

5. FILTER ONLY EMPTY CELLS

final_table_results = null_counts_long_df.filter(
    col("null_count") > 0
).select(
    col("table_name"),
    col("column_name"),
    col("null_count")
)

all_results.append(final_table_results)

6. COMBINE ALL RESULTS

if all_results:
  final_report_df = reduce(lambda df1, df2: df1.unionByName(df2), all_results)

  print("\n" + "" * 50)
  print("REPORT FINAL : COLUMNS WITH MISSING VALUES")
  print("" * 50)

  final_report_df.display()
else:
  print("\n No missing value found.")

4. Outlier Detection using SQL Statistics

Using SQL directly in Databricks, I identify transactions that significantly deviate from typical customer behaviour.

Outliers highlight:

abnormal spending amounts

categories where clients spend above the median

potential fraud, exceptional purchases, or high-value segments

This analysis is essential for building robust segmentation.

4.1. I will search for outliers.

For this task, using SQL, I will use statistics with MIN / MAX / AVERAGE / STANDARD DEVIATION / MEDIAN

MIN: There are negatives values

MAX: The max is much higher than the average value

MEDIAN: Median < Average -> So the data repartition is much lower than the average. And seeing the MAX is 160 times higher than the average, some data (outliers) are impacting significantly the average.

4.2. I will verify the data outliers distribution.

1. I will verify the outlier percentage versus the total number of transactions to have an overview. I can see 38% of the transaction amounts are above the average.

2. Below the detail of the outliers:

3. Focusing on outliers, I then verified the top 10 categories where the transaction amounts are higher than the median amount.

This query is displaying the categories in which people are able to spend amounts higher than the median (higher than the usual amount). It will be useful for segmentation and deep learning model creation.

4. I will examine the distribution data in the transaction table (based on fields containing 'id' , which are the keys to the 'fact' tables).

I see there are more than 13 million transactions done on 74K merchants and based only on 1,219 clients.
